ROOT CAUSE: `/work/src/be_code.c:461` in `exp2reg()`. When materializing a conditional/not expression into a register, the compiler emits the result into `reg = e->v.idx`, which is the source expression’s register. For `var j = !i` inside `f(i)`, `i` is a local in `R0`. `code_not()` marks the expression as a conditional-not expression without allocating a new destination. Later `be_code_setvar()` calls `exp2reg(finfo, e2, e1->v.idx)` with destination `R1` for `j`, but `exp2reg()` ignores that requested `dst` after `appendjump()` and uses `e->v.idx == R0`. The generated bytecode for `f(i)` writes `!i` into `R0`, then moves `R0` to `R1`, so the parameter `i` is changed from `1` to `false`; `return i` returns `false`, causing `assert(f(1) == 1)` to fail.

LOCAL FIX: In `exp2reg()`, after `appendjump()`, use the requested/materialized destination register instead of unconditionally using `e->v.idx`. Minimal replacement:
```diff
 static int exp2reg(bfuncinfo *finfo, bexpdesc *e, int dst)
 {
     int reg = var2reg(finfo, e, dst);
     if (hasjump(e)) { /* if conditional expression */
         int pcf = NO_JUMP;
         int pct = NO_JUMP;
         int jpt = appendjump(finfo, jumpboolop(e, 1), e);
-        reg = e->v.idx;
+        if (dst >= 0 && reg != dst) {
+            reg = dst;
+            if (dst >= finfo->freereg) {
+                be_code_allocregs(finfo, 1);
+            }
+        }
         be_code_conjump(finfo, &e->t, jpt);
         pcf = code_bool(finfo, reg, 0, 1);
         pct = code_bool(finfo, reg, 1, 0);
         patchlistaux(finfo, e->f, finfo->pc, pcf);
         patchlistaux(finfo, e->t, finfo->pc, pct);
         e->t = NO_JUMP;
         e->f = NO_JUMP;
         e->not = 0;
     }
     return reg;
 }
```
Equivalently, ensure `reg` remains the destination chosen by `var2reg()` and never gets overwritten with the operand register when converting boolean jump form into a concrete boolean value.

GLOBAL FIX: Separate “source operand register” from “destination/result register” in the compiler IR/API. `bexpdesc` currently reuses `v.idx` for locals, temporaries, constants, and expression results, which allowed unary `!` to alias its operand. Introduce an explicit result-register field or a bounded “register value” abstraction with an invariant that materializing an expression for assignment must not write into an unrelated local operand unless the destination is deliberately the same variable. Add compiler tests/disassembly assertions for aliasing cases such as `var j = !i; return i`, `var j = -i`, nested boolean expressions, and assignments to locals.

